{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:35:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:35:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14247"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14247"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.19,0.06,0.38,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6942"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103378"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6942"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85799"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103378"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of urinary frequency and burning on micturition. This is the third episode she has had in the last three months. She has no other symptoms and is otherwise in good health. Her medical history includes a laparoscopy for endometriosis six months ago. She does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable with no tenderness or masses. Urine is sent for analysis and in the interim a CT is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the abnormal CT findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crohn\u0027s disease","Diverticular disease","Carcinoma of the colon","Recurrent E. coli urinary tract infection","Endometriosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT shows gas in the bladder, a finding consistent with emphysematous cystitis. This condition is typically caused by gas-forming organisms, most commonly \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E. Given the patient\u0027s history of recurrent urinary tract infections, \u003Cstrong\u003Erecurrent E. coli urinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely explanation for the abnormal CT findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can occasionally lead to enterovesical fistulas, which could introduce gas into the bladder. However, this patient has no gastrointestinal symptoms, making Crohn\u0027s disease an unlikely explanation for the CT findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticular disease\u003C/strong\u003E is another potential cause of enterovesical fistulas. However, it typically affects older individuals and is usually accompanied by abdominal symptoms, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the colon\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause an enterovesical fistula, leading to gas in the bladder. However, this is unlikely in a 39-year-old woman without any concerning symptoms such as weight loss, change in bowel habits, or blood in the stool.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E, while present in the patient\u0027s history, is unlikely to cause gas in the bladder. Endometriosis can involve the bladder, but it does not typically result in gas formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmphysematous cystitis is an uncommon condition, most often seen in patients with diabetes or other immunocompromising conditions. In an otherwise healthy young woman with recurrent UTIs, the presence of gas in the bladder warrants consideration of underlying urinary tract anomalies or functional issues that may predispose her to recurrent infections. Further investigation with cystoscopy or urodynamic studies may be indicated if infections continue to recur despite appropriate antibiotic treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Emphysematous cystitis, characterised by gas in the bladder wall or lumen, is typically caused by gas-forming organisms like E. coli in urinary tract infections.","Recurrent urinary tract infections in young women may warrant investigation for underlying anatomical abnormalities or functional issues.","CT imaging can detect gas in the bladder, which may be due to infection, fistula, or iatrogenic causes."],"references":["Thomas AA, Lane BR, Thomas AZ, et al. Emphysematous cystitis: a review of 135 cases BJU 2007; 100:17-20.","Grayson DE, Abbott RM, Levy AD, Sherman PM. Emphysematous infections of the abdomen and pelvis: a pictorial review. Radiographics. 2002 May-Jun;22(3):543-61. doi: 10.1148/radiographics.22.3.g02ma06543. PMID: 12006686."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14247"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21078"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21078"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JMcwqtd7ITTEz79pDDatj4eJrA9Yoh.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JMcwqtd7ITTEz79pDDatj4eJrA9Yoh.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":910,"height":710}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T21:04:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T21:04:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6942"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103378"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji"